\name{uvmeta}
\alias{uvmeta}
\alias{uvmeta.default}
\alias{uvmetaMOM}
\alias{print.uvmeta}

\title{Univariate meta-analysis.}

\description{This function performs a univariate meta-analysis by assuming fixed or random effects.  Whereas the fixed effects model assumes that all studies in the analysis share a common effect size, the random-effects model allows different study-specific effect sizes. Concretely, if we move from fixed-effect weights to random-effects weights, large studies lose influence and small studies gain influence (Borenstein 2010). }

\usage{ uvmeta(r, vars, model="random", method="MOM", na.action, pars=list(quantiles = c(0.025, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 0.975), n.chains=4, n.adapt=5000, n.init=1000, n.iter=10000), verbose=FALSE, ...)}

\arguments{
  \item{\code{r}}{vector of numerics containing the effect sizes}
  \item{\code{vars}}{vector of numerics containing the error variance of the effect sizes}
  \item{\code{model}}{Assume random (\code{model="random"} (default) or fixed (\code{model="fixed"}) effects.}
  \item{\code{method}}{Estimation method. Use \code{method="MOM"} to implement the non-parametric method-of-moment estimator from DerSimonian and Laird. Altnernatively, use \code{method="bayes"} to perform a Bayesian meta-analysis that assumes normality of the random effects (Higgins 2009).}
  \item{na.action}{a function which indicates what should happen when the data contain NAs. Defaults to \code{na.fail}, other options are \code{na.omit}, \code{na.exclude} or \code{na.pass}.}
  \item{\code{pars}}{A list with additional arguments. Use \code{quantiles} to specify which confidence or credibility intervals should be calculated for parameter estimates. The following parameters configure the MCMC sampling procedure and are ignored if \code{method="MOM"}:  \code{n.chains} (specifies the number of parallel chains), \code{n.adapt} (specifies the number of iterations for adaptation), \code{n.init} (number of iterations to run for initializing the Markov chain) and \code{n.iter} (number of iterations to monitor).}
  \item{\code{verbose}}{if TRUE then messages generated during the fitting process will be displayed.}
  \item{\dots}{arguments to be passed on to other functions}
}

\details{The Bayesian approach uses an uninformative Normal prior for the mean and an uninformative uniform prior for the variance of the pooled effect size (Higgins 2009).  For random effects models, a prediction interval is calculated for the pooled effect size. This interval predicts in what range future effect sizes will fall given what has already been observed (based on a Student's t-distribution, cfr. Riley 2011).  
}

\value{ An object of the class \code{uvmeta} for which many standard methods are available. }

